        while (c) {
          c.frob();
        }
        result = baz(c);
    }</code></pre>

So I opened up one of my files and found the first instance of this. It was a function to load some subset of data and emit some log info. It was only called once, at the end of a chain of maps and filters.<p><pre><code>  let load_x xid = 
    // loading code

  // Later on...
  let data&#x27; = foo |> map ... |> filter ... |> ... |> map load_x
</code></pre>
Once you view functions as values like anything else, then making single-use, &quot;temporary&quot; functions seems as normal as temporary or intermediate variables.
